<DOC><DOCNO> AP890510-0238 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-10-89 0150EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     05-10 0644</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0681</SECOND><DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Financially troubled Pan Am Corp. said it mayoffer to buy much-larger NWA Inc., parent of Northwest Airlines andthe target of several other potential suitors.   Pan Am Chairman Thomas Plaskett did not provide details Tuesday,but said Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. was considering providingsignificant new equity for Pan Am so that it could make an all-cashoffer for NWA.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Trans World Airlines Inc. said it was notprepared to submit a formal bid for strikebound Eastern Airlines.   Takeover strategist Carl C. Icahn, the owner and chairman ofTWA, has held numerous discussions with officials of Eastern'sunions and had been widely expected to make a bid for theMiami-based airline.   TWA said Tuesday it needed more time to discuss the idea withits unions.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Viacom Inc. has sued Time Inc. in federal courtfor $2.4 billion in antitrust damages, accusing its rival ofmonopolizing pay television.   Viacom Inc. is parent of Showtime-The Movie Channel and Timeowns Home Box Office as well as major cable operators.   Time blasted Viacom's suit on Tuesday as baseless.</TEXT><DATELINE>CORNELIUS, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Oregon farmers have planted 18 percentless land in strawberries this year because of fluctuations in themigrant work force and complications of the new federal immigrationlaw.   The harvest may cover even less acreage if more migrant pickersdon't arrive in the next few weeks for the June picking.   Under a 1986 law, employers face fines of up to $10,000 for eachillegal worker they hire.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   In a bid to generate excitement for CBS' falltelevision programs and gain publicity for K mart Corp., the TVnetwork and the retailer plan a big national promotion tied to theSeptember premiere of CBS shows.   The promotion will be built around a viewer involvement game.   K mart and CBS will alert viewers in print and via electronicmedia how to play and which shows to watch.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The U.S. electronics industry has released aplan proposing more than $1.3 billion in government aid to helpAmerica catch up in the global race to develop high-definitiontelevision technology.   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher, however, said Tuesday U.S.manufacturers shouldn't depend on Uncle Sam to be their ``UncleSugar'' in bankrolling the effort.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A government study suggests that the Sematechresearch consortium is no guarantee the United States will capturethe commercial edge in production of semiconductor chips.   The Commerce Department study said Tuesday a host of trade, taxand antitrust issues will continue to affect the competitiveness ofU.S. chipmakers, regardless of the success of the Austin, Texas,consortium.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The nation's 100 biggest black-owned industrialand service companies grew 14.4 percent in revenue last year,topping the 7.6 percent growth of the Fortune 500, according toBlack Enterprise magazine.   The companies achieved the revenue growth despite streamliningefforts that trimmed their employment rolls by 21.7 percent, themagazine reported in releasing the list Tuesday.</TEXT><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The British government said it would grant SouthAfrican-controlled Minorco SA a limited extension in its hostile$5.8 billion bid for Britain's Consolidated Gold Fields PLC.   The Panel on Takeovers and Mergers on Tuesday also ordered GoldFields to discontinue its court proceedings against Minorco unlessits shareholders approve such actions at a May 30 meeting.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Stock prices fell in sluggish trading Tuesday.The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 5.14 points to2,371.33, its eighth consecutive decline.   The dollar retreated slightly.   Bond prices dropped sharply. The yield on the Treasury'sbenchmark 30-year bond, which rises when the price falls, climbedto 9.09 percent from 8.99 percent.   Coffee futures prices climbed and petroleum futures rebounded.</TEXT></DOC>